Anonymous Thu 18 Aug 2022 23:11:19 No.50268369 Report
Quoted By:
>>50268052
>How do other writers pull through
I'm bad at quitting.
I tossed four months of work - almost 130k words - on the scrap pile because the plot didn't match the characters. Two or three times a week, I'd have an idea about what was wrong, work on that, rinse & repeat.
I had thought before that point that I was disciplined and able to tackle any idea I had. Learning how to make that cut-off decision (and most of the characters & plot will get used in due time) taught me more than completing two novel-length pieces.

I learned to believe in myself because I believed in the characters. I learned to love and stop calling my sappy ideas cringe.
I learned the only thing stopping me, was me.

Anonymous Thu 18 Aug 2022 23:24:06 No.50268637 Report
Quoted By: >>50268772
>>50268052
you want to write?
>set out an hour every day to sit in front of your computer
>have whatever writing application you use open, don't look at the internet or phone or tv
>if you don't write you just stare at a blank screen for a fucking hour.

you'll write anything, and it'll likely suck, but just do it every day.
leave yourself time after the hour in case you want to keep going.
but never do less than the hour unless it's an emergency or something.
this is your post and you don't abandon your post.

no one has to see what you write unless you share it.
so just sit on it for as long as you want.
you'll think about stuff after sleeping or even several days later.
if some part of your writing really bothers you read over it and try to write again.

keep edits short, and if you discover "everything is wrong" don't get discouraged.
save and close what you wrote as is, open a new document.
try re-writing the section from scratch.
and again wait a day or two to compare.

just because a story is linear doesn't mean you have to write it that way.
if you think of a scene that excites you write it out, even if it's the climactic ending.
it can be a brief summery or go into detail, you can use placeholder characters and places, whatever.
any idea can be turned upside down, reworked, or discarded whenever you want.

Something I like to do when I get stuck is simply look at where I'm at in the outline, look at what happens next, then gradually expand out from the next section of the outline. For example

Anon meets his waifur

becomes

Anon runs into his waifur in a busy airport

becomes

Anon blitzes through the busy terminal dodging other passengers as he misses his flight and crashes into his waifur.

becomes

Gate B12? Or was it A12? Anon looks at his smudged ticket unable to discern the answer. With time running out he makes a quick coin flip in his head and it comes up with B12. Objective set he runs towards the gate with wreckless abandon, suitcase rattling loudly behind him. He gracefully dodges an elephantine woman then not so gracefully dodges a tall Lioness, hitting her in the shins with his heavy suitcase. With a half hearted "Sorry!" he doesn't dare look back at the growling feline as he continues his sprint. Based on the signs he should be getting close to his gate. Just have to round this final corner and-

"Ow!"

Something soft and furry impacts his chest and he falls down onto the polished floor. After gathering his senses he leans up to see a towering tomboy childhood friend wolf woman in a TSA uniform.

"My god, waifur? Is that really you? It's been years." He says.

The waifur simply licks her lips with a devious smile.

"Excuse me sir, you've randomly chosen for a penis inspection. Please follow me to the penis inspection room."

"No! No! Please! I have to catch my flight! I've got to make it to the important business meeting to discuss business!"

She smiles.

"Sorry sir, but I think it's going to be 'me' meeting your 'business' today." She says, grabbing him by the collar and dragging him across the floor.

"Oh no how terrible why is my beloved childhood friend trying to see my penis oh no blah blah blah"

Anonymous Fri 19 Aug 2022 06:08:36 No.50275762 Report
Quoted By: >>50282840
>>50272562
>they had to write characters that fit the world/setting.
Not entirely sure what you mean by this. Science fiction is a very broad category and virtually any type of setting is possible. Don't want to put words in your mouth but it seems to me that you may be equating science fiction with military sci-fi or space opera. Ursula LeGuin was writing sociological science fiction with a feminist slant in the 60s, Alice Bradley Sheldon was writing about gender norms and female oppression as James Tiptree Jr. Lots of male authors were tackling social issues with science fiction, too, and focusing on human connections rather than combat or pure technology, like John Varley who wrote frequently about gender, free love, and family structures in the future. The only uphill battle female authors faced (aside from the stigma sci-fi carried as generally being for kids and nerds) was a male audience and editors who believed they weren't good enough, which resulted in many female authors having successful careers while publishing under male names or their initials. (C.J. Cherryh, C.L. Moore, Robin Hobb, etc.) Joanna Russ was very, very far from being the only successful feminist sci-fi writer who integrated those themes in her worldbuilding.
